  "html_url": "https://github.com/algolia/instantsearch/issues/6608",
  "title": "Refinements Are Erased from URL When No Results Are Found",
  "body": "### 🐛 Current behavior\n\nWhen using a custom filter implementation on the /search page ```(fetching facets from _rawResults)```, the applied filters ```(facetFilters)``` are removed from the URL when a search returns no results. This does not happen on the /category page, where Algolia's built-in RefinementList widget is used.\n\n### 🔍 Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Go to /search and enter a search query.\n2. Apply a filter from the custom filter UI.\n3. If results exist, the filters remain in the URL.\n4. If no results are found, the search re-triggers an API request without facetFilters, removing them from the URL.\n5. Compare this behavior with /category, where the facetFilters remain intact.\n\n### Live reproduction\n\nhttps://codesandbox.io/p/github/daryldeogracias/algolia-web-app/chore/refinementlist\n\n### 💭 Expected behavior\n\n1. `facetFilters` should persist in the URL even when no results are found, just like on the /category page.\n2.  and it should not  re-trigger a search request when no results are found.\n\n### Package version\n\n\"next\": \"^15.1.6\", \"react-instantsearch\": \"^7.15.3\", \"react-instantsearch-nextjs\": \"^0.4.4\", \"algoliasearch\": \"^5.20.0\", \"instantsearch.js\": \"^4.77.3\",\n\n### Operating system\n\nmacOS 15.3.1 (24D70)\n\n### Browser\n\nChrome Version 133.0.6943.142\n\n### Code of Conduct\n\n- [x] I agree to follow this project's Code of Conduct",
